{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14189"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14189"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.03,0.14,0.29,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-09-17T07:44:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T16:20:58+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-09-17T07:55:18+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-19 12:33:21"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14189"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84094"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"3229"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35011"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84094"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with involuntary movements of her mouth and tongue that have been present for the past six months. She has a history of treatment-resistant schizophrenia and has tried multiple antipsychotics over the past 10 years, including risperidone, olanzapine and haloperidol, with inadequate response. She is currently taking aripiprazole and reports ongoing positive schizophrenic symptoms affecting her quality of life . She has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are visible choreiform movements of her lips and tongue, which worsen when she is distracted. Her psychiatrist has diagnosed tardive dyskinesia and is considering treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Switch to clozapine","Increase aripiprazole dose","Start tetrabenazine","Begin benztropine","Switch to haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with tardive dyskinesia (TD) in the context of treatment-resistant schizophrenia. The management of this complex situation requires careful consideration of both the movement disorder and the underlying psychiatric condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to clozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in this case. Clozapine is considered the gold standard for treatment-resistant schizophrenia, which this patient has demonstrated by failing to respond adequately to multiple antipsychotics. Moreover, clozapine has a lower risk of causing or exacerbating tardive dyskinesia compared to other antipsychotics. While clozapine is not a specific treatment for TD, its use may allow for better control of psychiatric symptoms while minimizing the risk of worsening the movement disorder. The potential benefits of improved psychiatric control with clozapine outweigh the risks in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting tetrabenazine\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially beneficial for managing TD symptoms, does not address the underlying treatment-resistant schizophrenia. Tetrabenazine is a vesicular monoamine transporter 2 (VMAT2) inhibitor that can help with movement disorders, but it does not have antipsychotic properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the aripiprazole dose\u003C/strong\u003E would likely worsen the tardive dyskinesia. While aripiprazole has a relatively low risk of causing TD compared to some other antipsychotics, increasing the dose of any antipsychotic in the presence of TD is generally not recommended as the medication is already likely the cause of the TD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeginning benztropine\u003C/strong\u003E (an anticholinergic) is not recommended for tardive dyskinesia. While anticholinergics can be helpful for acute dystonic reactions, they are generally ineffective for TD and may even exacerbate symptoms in some cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate. Haloperidol is a high-potency typical antipsychotic that carries a higher risk of causing or worsening tardive dyskinesia compared to atypical antipsychotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of tardive dyskinesia in the context of treatment-resistant schizophrenia involves a careful balance between treating the underlying psychiatric condition and managing the movement disorder. Switching to clozapine addresses the primary issue of treatment-resistant schizophrenia while potentially stabilizing or improving the TD symptoms. Close monitoring for both psychiatric symptoms and movement disorder will be crucial during the transition to clozapine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clozapine is often considered for treatment-resistant schizophrenia and has a lower risk of causing or worsening tardive dyskinesia compared to other antipsychotics.","Management of treatment-resistant schizophrenia with tardive dyskinesia requires careful balance between psychiatric symptoms and movement disorder.","Tetrabenazine, while effective for tardive dyskinesia, does not address the underlying psychiatric condition."],"references":["Galletly C, Castle D, Dark F, Humberstone V, Jablensky A, Killackey E, Kulkarni J, McGorry P, Nielssen O, Tran N. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the management of schizophrenia and related disorders. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2016 May;50(5):410-72."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84094"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14189"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84094"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T16:20:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T16:21:31+09:30","number":11,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-05-03T16:20:55+09:30","plagiarismScore":4.5,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-6872-11.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T055856Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=30a7d28f5e4af32e90b5096499312e35c6c8ccffebb96e60f2a5885cd10fec16"},"relationships":{"item":{"d